      </ul>

      <h2>Insurance Optimization: How to Reduce Premiums</h2>

      <h3>Strategy 1: Fleet Discounts</h3>

      <p>Insurers offer 10-20% discounts for fleets of 5+ vehicles:
      <br>• Standard single policy: RM10,000/year
      <br>• Fleet discount (5 lorries): RM8,000-9,000/year
      <br><strong>Annual Savings:</strong>RM5,000-10,000 per policy</p>

      <h3>Strategy 2: Safety Features Reduce Premiums</h3>

      <p>Invest in safety technology (often required by financing anyway):
      <br>• GPS tracking: -5% to -10% premium
      <br>• Dash cameras: -5% to -8% premium
      <br>• Speed limiters: -3% to -5% premium
      <br>• Driver training programs: -3% to -5% premium</p>

      <p><strong>Technology Cost vs Premium Savings:</strong>
      <br>• GPS unit: RM1,000 one-time, saves RM500-1,000 annually
      <br>• Dash cam: RM800 one-time, saves RM400-800 annually
      <br><strong>ROI:</strong> 1-2 years to recover cost, then pure savings</p>

      <h3>Strategy 3: Higher Deductibles = Lower Premiums</h3>

      <p>Accept higher deductibles to reduce premiums:
      <br>• Standard deductible: RM1,000 per claim
      <br>• High deductible: RM5,000-RM10,000 per claim
      <br>• Premium reduction: 15-25%</p>

      <p><strong>Caveat:</strong> Ensure you can afford RM10,000 out-of-pocket per claim before choosing high deductibles.</p>

      <h2>Financing vs Paying Cash: Which Makes Sense?</h2>

      <h3>Pay Cash Approach</h3>

      <p><strong>Pros:</strong>
      <br>• No interest costs
      <br>• Full ownership of insurance policies
      <br>• Can change insurers annually</p>

      <p><strong>Cons:</strong>
      <br>• Large upfront cash outflow (RM70,000+ annually)
      <br>• Capital tied up in prepayments
      <br>• Inflation increases these fixed costs over time
      <br>• Opportunity cost (cash could earn returns elsewhere)</p>

      <h3>Financing (Bundled) Approach</h3>

      <p><strong>Pros:</strong>
      <br>• No large upfront cash outflow
      <br>• Fixed monthly payment simplifies budgeting
      <br>• Interest tax-deductible (business expense)
      <br>• Preserves working capital for operations</p>

      <p><strong>Cons:</strong>
      <br>• Interest costs apply
      <br>• Less flexibility to change insurers annually</p>

      <h3>Decision Framework</h3>

      <p><strong>If Paying Cash:</strong>
      <br>• Requires consistent cash reserves
      <br>• Must have RM70,000+ available annually for insurance/tax
      <br>• Capital could earn returns if invested elsewhere</p>

      <p><strong>If Financing (Bundled):</strong>
      <br>• 0% down payment preserves capital
